{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Use British English|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = Lady | name = Aileen Fox | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Aileen Henderson | birth_date = 29 July 1907 | birth_place = London, England | death_date = {{death-date and age|21 November 2005|29 July 1907}} | death_place = Exeter, England | death_cause = | resting_place = | residence = | alma_mater = [[Newnham College, Cambridge]] | occupation = Archaeologist | years_active = | employer = | known_for = | notable_works = | awards = FSA | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Aileen Mary Fox''', Lady Fox, [[Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (née Henderson, 29 July 1907 – 21 November 2005), was an English archaeologist.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Allen |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article333431.ece |title=Aileen Fox: Founder of modern archaeology in south-western England' |work=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=16 December 2005 |accessdate=22 November 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051218023204/http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article333431.ece |archivedate=18 December 2005 }}</ref> She specialised in the archaeology of South West England, notably excavating the Roman legionary fortress in [[Exeter]] in Devon after World War II.
==Biography== The daughter of a solicitor, she was educated at [[Chinthurst School]] in Surrey and later at [[Downe House School]] in Kent. She remained at the school after it moved to Berkshire, under the headship of [[Olive Willis]], and then went on to read English at [[Newnham College, Cambridge]].{{sfn|Fox|2000|page=25}}{{sfn|Fox|2000|page=27}}<ref name="times">{{cite news|title=Aileen Fox|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=21 December 2005|page=48}}</ref> After her graduation in 1929, she worked as a volunteer on the excavation of [[Richborough]], Kent, under J. P. Bushe-Fox.<ref name=times/> She spent the following winter at the [[British School at Rome]], before returning to [[Richborough]].<ref name=obituary>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/jan/20/guardianobituaries.obituaries|title=Obituary: Aileen Fox|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 January 2006|first=Henrietta|last=Quinnell}}</ref> In 1932 she excavated at [[Hembury|Hembury hillfort]], [[Devon]] and Meon Hill, [[Hampshire]].<ref name=obituary/>
In 1933 she married [[Cyril Fox]], the director of the [[National Museum Wales|National Museum of Wales]], with whom she had three sons. The Foxes excavated prehistoric and Roman sites throughout the UK, although Fox continued to lead her own excavations, such as at the Roman legionary fortress at [[Isca Augusta]] (Caerleon, Wales) in 1939.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fox|first1=Aileen|title=The legionary fortress at Caerleon, Monmouthshire: Excavations in Myrtle Cottage Orchard 1939|journal=Archaeologia Cambrensis|volume=95|pages=101–52}}</ref> Fox lectured at the University College, [[Cardiff]], from 1940 to 1945.<ref name=obituary/> Her most notable achievement was her three seasons of excavation at Roman [[Exeter]], following damage from [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Aileen|title=Roman Exeter (Isca Dumnoniorum): excavations in the war-damaged areas, 1945-1947|date=1952|publisher=Published for the University College of the South-West of England by Manchester University Press|location=Manchester}}</ref> Following these excavations, she took up a lectureship at the [[University of Exeter#University College of the South West of England|University College of the South West of England]] at Exeter in 1947, and stayed until her retirement in 1971.<ref name=obituary/> From the late 1940s onwards, she undertook key excavations in south-west England, shedding new light on prehistoric occupation of [[Dartmoor]], Iron Age hillforts in the region and the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] military presence in [[Cornwall]].<ref name="Quinnell2013">{{cite book|title=Oxford dictionary of national biography 2005-2008|last=Quinnell|first=Henrietta|date=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|page=398|editor1-last=Goldman|editor1-first=Lawrence}}</ref>
In 1965, she was a founding member of the Hillforts Study Group, alongside [[Christopher Hawkes]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hillfortsstudygroup.org.uk/|title=The Hillfort Study Group}}</ref> In the late 1960s, Fox played a key role in establishing the Exeter Archaeological Field Unit. She served as the president of the Devon Archaeological Society (1963-64) and as a vice-president of the [[Council for British Archaeology]].<ref name=Quinnell2013/> She believed in the nurturing of archaeological interest in the young, and produced her book ''Roman Britain'' in collaboration with the artist [[Alan Sorrell]], whom she had met many years earlier at the [[British School at Rome]]. Following her husband's knighthood in 1935, she became known as Lady Fox.
==Awards and recognition== In 1944, Fox was elected to a fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]].<ref name=Quinnell2013/> In 1985 she was awarded an honorary doctorate of letters from the [[University of Exeter]] <ref name=Quinnell2013/> and in 1998 honorary membership of [[the Prehistoric Society]].<ref name=Quinnell2013/>
