{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}} {{Infobox ancient site | name = Enkapune Ya Muto | native_name = | alternate_name =Twilight Cave | image = | alt = | caption = | image_size = 240 | map_type =Kenya | map_alt = Enkapune Ya Muto | map_caption = location in Kenya | map_size = 240 | relief = yes | coordinates = {{coord|0|38|47|N|36|3|15|E|display=inline,title}}<!-- EDITORIAL NOTE: coords not correct--> | location = [[Mau Escarpment]] of [[Kenya]] | region = [[Kenya]] | type = | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | depth = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = | cultures = | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | website = | notes = }} '''Enkapune Ya Muto''', also known as '''Twilight Cave''', is a [[Late Stone Age]] site on the [[Mau Escarpment]] of [[Kenya]]. Beads made of perforated ostrich egg shells found at the site have been dated to 40,000 years ago. The beads found at the site represent the early human use of [[Jewelry|personal ornaments]].<ref name="MyUser_Archaeology.about.com_March_7_2017c">{{cite web |url=http://archaeology.about.com/od/eterms/g/enkapune_ya_mut.htm |title=Enkapune Ya Muto Rockshelter - Enkapune Ya Muto |publisher=Archaeology.about.com |date= |author= |accessdate= March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Hunter to herder: large mammal remains from the hunter-gatherer occupation at Enkapune Ya Muto rock-shelter, Central Rift, Kenya |doi=10.1007/BF01117697 |year=1992 |url=http://www.springerlink.com/content/g00l340q07p4g206/ |author=Marean, Curtis W. |journal=The African Archaeological Review |volume=10 |pages=65 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Chronology of the Later Stone Age and Food Production in East Africa |doi=10.1006/jasc.1997.0277 |year=1997 |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6WH8-45J568C-2G&_user=10&_rdoc=1&_fmt=&_orig=search&_sort=d&v